When using GNOME
If you’re using GNOME, you can remap the &lt;Caps_Lock&gt; key by following these steps:

install gnome-tweaks;
go to Keyboard and Mouse;
go to Additional Layout Options;
click on Caps Lock behavior;
click on Make Caps Lock an additional Esc.

Note that this method may not work in Hyper-V, but it should work in VMware.


When using i3
If you’re using i3, add this to the end of your i3 configuration file ~/.config/i3/config:
exec --no-startup-id setxkbmap -option caps:escape
To take effect, you have to restart i3. You can do this by logging out and logging back.

Casting: Telling the compiler that an object is really something else without changing it (though some data loss may be incurred).
object obj_s= "12345";
string str_i = (string) obj; // "12345" as string, explicit

int small = 12345;
long big = 0;
big = small; // 12345 as long, implicit
Parsing: Telling the program to interpret (on runtime) a string.
string int_s = "12345";
int i = int.Parse(int_s); // 12345 as int
Converting: Telling the program to use built in methods to try to change type for what may be not simply interchangeable.
double dub = 123.45;
int i = System.Convert.ToInt32(dub); // 123 as int

